{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","data":{"body":"DRIFT ASSESSMENT + PROPOSED CHANGES (2026-07-13) — after both prerequisite epics shipped.\n\nVERDICT: The epic's DESIGN remains correct and the goal is unchanged. But its plan pre-dated the\ndelivery of both prerequisites, so it over-scoped itself: it declared \"independent of the identity\nepic\" and planned to build a merge-gate, a merged-log ledger, and era-scoped key rotation from\nscratch — all of which the identity epic (e68d/gnu-whale-ichor) has since SHIPPED and are reusable.\nI remediated the trivial factual drift inline (see below) and propose the scope changes here.\n\nTRIVIAL DRIFT REMEDIATED IN-LINE (description + file_impact edited):\n- The blanket \"independent of the identity epic\" now reads as actor/threat-model orthogonality\n  (different key/trust-root/namespace) + \"dependency never inverted\", NOT \"no shared code\".\n- Named the shipped mechanisms the plan spoke of abstractly: merge-gate = verify-identity.yaml;\n  era-scoped validity = attest/authorship.py commit-ancestry positions (added_at_commit/\n  revoked_at_commit via `git merge-base --is-ancestor`); verdict key_not_valid_at_era already in\n  schemas/verify_signature_result.schema.json; substrate = src/rebar/attest/ (not signing.py);\n  HMAC-legacy = attest/hmac_legacy.py in registry.py POLICY.\n- file_impact: substrate corrected to src/rebar/attest/; workflow entry now says \"extend\n  verify-identity.yaml, not a parallel job\".\n- Added a \"Prerequisites shipped\" drift note block at the top of Context.\n- NOTE: the description edit makes the existing plan-review attestation read as STALE (material\n  changed) — expected; re-run `rebar review-plan` before claiming.\n\nPROPOSED SCOPE CHANGES (need owner decision — not applied to children yet):\n1. Child 4214 (merge-gate CI job): re-scope from \"new CI job over the merged log\" to \"add an\n   op-cert lane to / mirror the shipped verify-identity gate\". The merged-log walk + ENFORCE_SINCE\n   grandfathering already exist; op-cert should reuse them. Big net-code reduction.\n2. Child 5893 (env-key era-scoped rotation): re-scope from \"build era-scoped validity\" to \"reuse\n   attest/authorship.py's commit-ancestry validity, applied to the environment keyring\". This may\n   shrink 5893 from a full mechanism to a thin adapter — consider merging it into child 368c\n   (the kind + subject binding) if little unique work remains.\n3. Reuse key_not_valid_at_era verdict from the shared schema (already present) rather than adding\n   a new op-cert-specific verdict.\n\nSTILL GENUINELY NET-NEW (unchanged by the prerequisites — the real remaining work):\n- 368c: rebar.opcert.v1 Ed25519 kind + {ticket,material,merged-log-position} subject binding.\n- 42d1: out-of-band trusted-env key pinning + verify-against-pinned-key (op-cert trust root is\n  OUT-OF-BAND/high-authority — deliberately unlike identity's in-band TOFU keys; NOT delivered by\n  identity, must preserve this distinction).\n- ee0b: trusted rebar-mcp remote-execution + AWS infra (authoritative-state fetch).\n- 8f1d: HMAC removal (contract phase).\n- 6a89: docs + ADR.\n\nCAVEAT to check before claiming 4214/5893: the identity epic's own completion comments flagged\nsome deliver-vs-spec gaps (e.g. AC7 CLI naming, whether key_not_valid_at_era was folded into the\nSHARED schema vs a local vocab). The schema file DOES now contain key_not_valid_at_era, so that\none resolved — but confirm the reused surfaces are the shared ones before depending on them."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1783959740593659001,"uuid":"23e91169-7fdf-4063-90c1-c34fc835e5d3"}